<div id="review_728826273" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/728826273" />
    <a title="Max" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8079403-max"><img alt="Max" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625519120p2/8079403.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/728826273?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Max" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Max" href="/user/show/8079403-max">Max</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8079403-max?shelf=european-history">european-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer728826273" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2726087141665036459">The Proud Tower: A Portrait of the World Before the War 1890-1914 puts too much detail in too few pages. Many people are mentioned with little to distinguish their relative importance, often just a name with a couple of salient facts. Conversely Tuchman’s prior book, The Guns of August, focuses on a single month with extensive profiling of key players creating a clear picture of people and issues.<br/><br/>At times it feels like Tuchman expects the reader to already be familiar with everyone she cites. If</span>
  <span id="freeText2726087141665036459" style="display:none">The Proud Tower: A Portrait of the World Before the War 1890-1914 puts too much detail in too few pages. Many people are mentioned with little to distinguish their relative importance, often just a name with a couple of salient facts. Conversely Tuchman’s prior book, The Guns of August, focuses on a single month with extensive profiling of key players creating a clear picture of people and issues.<br /><br />At times it feels like Tuchman expects the reader to already be familiar with everyone she cites. If you are not, remembering who they are and placing them in context is challenging. Even some major figures of the period are dealt with very summarily. For example rendering Chancellor von Bulow in several paragraphs and his aid Holstein in one is so superficial as to hardly be worth the effort, yet these were exceptionally important people of the period. <br /><br />Robert Massie’s book, Dreadnought, which covered the same period, was much better executed because it concentrated its focus on key players and events for which he provided sufficient detail to make them meaningful, memorable and interesting. Luckily I read Massie’s book just before Tuchman’s which enabled me to understand and connect many of the people Tuchman mentions in ways I could not have done otherwise. <br /><br />The space devoted to the peace movements and conferences seemed out of proportion to their significance. The peace conferences seemed more of a sideshow except as they were used for diplomatic posturing. Diplomacy constituted the significant efforts towards peace and its failure resulted in war as did the rabid nationalism that took over Germany. But much more space was devoted to the doves and social reformers. As a portrait of the times, The Proud Tower’s focus seemed scattered.<br /><br />With all that said there were a couple of sections I thought very worthwhile. One was the section on the Dreyfus affair and its role as a proxy for divisions in French society much as Obamacare is in the USA as I write this. Another was the section on Speaker of the House Tom Reed, showing the political games in America over 100 years ago were the same as they are today. This section also nicely highlighted the inherent change in the United States’ world role that was embedded in the decision to engage in the Spanish American war. In both these sections she was able to bring unity to her presentation and give context to the details by tying them neatly to a central theme.<br /><br />Barbara Tuchman can write fantastically well. The Guns of August is a wonderfully spun narrative that I enjoyed very much. The Proud Tower simply didn’t measure up to the very high standard she herself set. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2726087141665036459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


